Introduction

This assignment evaluates 5 different models estimating the price of subaru vehicles. This is the same data set that we worked on last week. This analysis will evaluate the models, and then pick the best ones and compare them on a few different metrics.

Measures of Accuracy

The following code takes three measures of accuracy on each of the five models estimating the price of the subaru vehicle. The highest MAE value is 4111 from the fourth model, while the lowest is 1478 which is from the third model. The highest rmse is from the fourth model and the lowest is from the third model. The R^2 is also the same with the highest error coming from the fourth model and lowest from the third. The two lowest MAE values are from models 3 and 2 at 1478 and 1834, respectively. The lowest RMSE values are from models 3 and 2 at 2414 and 3041, respectively. Lastly, the highest R^2 values come from models 3 and 2 at 0.870 and 0.795, meaning that models 3 and 2 account for 87% and 79.5% of the variance in the actual price, respectively. In conclusion, models 2 and 3 are the best of the five models. Model 4 was the worst. The code also uses the mean percentage error (MPE) as a measure of accuracy. This calculates the mean percentage difference between the actual and predicted prices of that model. Interestingly, models 3 and 5 had the lowest MPE at -2341% and -2232%, respectively. This is quite a large difference in the average percentage of the actual and predicted values. Overall, the measures of accuracy show that the models are not great predictors of the price, but models 2 and 3 are still the best.

# Model 1

training_price_estimates <- read.table("training_price_estimates.txt", header = TRUE, sep = "\t")

predictedvalues1 <- training_price_estimates$model1_est

# Calculate RMSE
rmse1 <- sqrt(mean((training_price_estimates$price - predictedvalues1)^2, na.rm = TRUE))
cat("RMSE:", rmse1, "\n")
## RMSE: 3475.651
mae1 <- mean(abs(training_price_estimates$price - training_price_estimates$model1_est), na.rm = TRUE)
cat("MAE:", mae1, "\n")
## MAE: 2333.013
# Calculate R-squared 

train.lm <- lm(price ~ model1_est, data = training_price_estimates)

r_squared1 <- summary(train.lm)$r.squared

cat("R-squared:", r_squared1, "\n")
## R-squared: 0.7288617
# Calculate MPE
mpe1 <- mean((training_price_estimates$price - training_price_estimates$model1_est) / training_price_estimates$price, na.rm = TRUE) * 100
cat("MPE:", mpe1, "%\n")
## MPE: -2985.74 %

Best Models: 2 & 3

The first step in evaluating the top 2 models is to see how they perform across car models. The smallest RMSE values are in the impreza and legacy estimates. The smallest MAE values are also seen in the impreza and legacy models. However, model 3 is the most accurate for the impreza and forester models. Both of the plots display similar linear relationships across the models when compared to the actual values.

price_estimates <- read.table("price_estimates.txt", header = TRUE, sep = "\t")

plot(price_estimates$price, price_estimates$model3_est)

The next step is to evaluate the top 2 models across the years. The second model had the smallest RMSE values in years 1994 and 1996 at 400 and 814, respectively. The smallest MAE values are in 1994 and 1997. 1996 is 670 and 1997 is 644. 1994 is also 400. The smallest RMSE values are in 1997 (698) and 1994 (309). These are significantly smaller than the RMSE values in the second model. The smallest MAE values are in 1994 (309) and 1997 (686). When looking at the plots, model 2 appears to have more variability across the years when comparing the actual vs.predicted prices.

The final step in evaluating the top 2 models is to see how they perform across the odometer readings. The tables created showing the odometer readings is difficult because it shows it across every reading. Therefore, this section will use the plots below. There is much more variability in the 2nd model across the odometer compared to the 3rd model. We can see this by the points being closer together and showing a stronger linear relationship in model 3. They both have outliers. Lastly, both have much stronger correlation in the lower price values. As the values get larger, the less data points and the more variability.
